{"title_page": "Richard Hely-Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Donoughmore \n| honorific-suffix = [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order1 = [[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| term_start1 = 3 March 1859\n| term_end1 = 11 June 1859\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 14th Earl of Derby|The Earl of Derby]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Joseph Warner Henley]]\n| successor1 = [[Thomas Milner Gibson]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|4 April 1823|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|22 February 1866|4 April 1823}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]  \n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = Thomasina Steele (d. 1890) \n}}\n\n'''Richard John Hely-Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore''' [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (4 April 1823 \u2013 22 February 1866), styled '''Viscount Suirdale''' between 1832 and 1851, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nDonoughmore was the son of [[John Hely-Hutchinson, 3rd Earl of Donoughmore]], and the Hon. Margaret, daughter of [[Luke Gardiner, 1st Viscount Mountjoy]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11063.htm |title= thepeerage.com Richard John Hely Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore of Knocklofty |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nDonoughmore was appointed [[High Sheriff of Tipperary]] for 1847.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.freemasonry.london.museum/os/wp-content/resources/frs_freemasons_complete_jan2012.pdf| title = Fellows of the Royal Society who are or were Freemasons, listed alphabetically| accessdate = 2012-11-09| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121202144502/http://www.freemasonry.london.museum/os/wp-content/resources/frs_freemasons_complete_jan2012.pdf| archivedate = 2012-12-02}}</ref>\n\nHe entered the [[House of Lords]] on the death of his father in 1851. He held office as [[Vice-President of the Board of Trade]] and [[Paymaster General]] in [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 14th Earl of Derby|Lord Derby]]'s [[Conservative Government 1858\u20131859|second government]], and was promoted to the actual [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry|presidency of the Board of Trade]] in February 1859 on the resignation of [[Joseph Warner Henley|J. W. Henley]] over the abortive 1859 Reform Bill. He remained in this post until the government fell in June of the same year. In 1858 he was admitted to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]].<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/22125/pages/1792 ''The London Gazette'', 9 April 1858]</ref>\n\nIn 1865 he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=8&dsqSearch=%28%28Gender%3D%27Male%27%29AND%28Surname%3D%27hutchinson%27%29%29| title = Library and Archive Catalogue|publisher = Royal Society|accessdate = 2012-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Donoughmore married Thomasina Jocelyn, daughter of Walter Steele, in 1847. Their fifth son the Hon. [[Walter Hely-Hutchinson|Sir Walter Hely-Hutchinson]] was a diplomat. Donoughmore died in February 1866, aged 42, and was succeeded in the earldom by his eldest son, [[John Hely-Hutchinson, 5th Earl of Donoughmore|John]]. The Countess of Donoughmore died in May 1890.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11063.htm |title= thepeerage.com Richard John Hely Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore of Knocklofty |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>\n\nColonel [[Lewis Vivian Loyd]] was married on 14 August 1879 to Lady Mary Sophia Hely Hutchinson (1854\u20131936), daughter of the 4th Earl of Donoughmore, <ref name=\"ThePeerage\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25089.htm#i250890\n|title=Colonel Lewis Vivian Loyd\n|work=ThePeerage.com\n|accessdate=28 June 2010\n}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref> a writer and translator<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.whistler.arts.gla.ac.uk/correspondence/biog/display/?bid=Loyd_M\n|title=Mary S. Loyd, 1854-1936\n|work=The Correspondence of James McNeill Whistler\n|accessdate=28 June 2010\n}}</ref> with whom he had three children: two sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9UYYThhRIQC&pg=PA297&lpg=PA297&dq=%22Lewis+Vivian+Loyd%22&source=bl&ots=mnao9-Vbwa&sig=ydTOuJmiAFJvxZg-DZRFyqonfr8&hl=en&ei=dPcoTO22N87KjAf1qtFq&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBQQ6AEwADge#v=onepage&q=%22Lewis%20Vivian%20Loyd%22&f=false\n|title=Plantagenet Roll of the Blood Royal: The Clarence Volume, Containing the Descendants of George, Duke of Clarence\n|last=Melville Henry Massue Ruvigny et Raineval (marquis de)\n|year=1994\n|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com\n|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Freemasonry==\nHe was Intitated in Lodge No.12, in Ireland and was Senior Grand Warden of the Grand Lodge of Ireland for 1846.. He was made an Honorary Member of Lodge Holyrood House (St Luke's), No.44, on 7 January 1846.<ref>A History of the Mason Lodge of Holyrood House (St.Luke's), No.44, holding of the Grand Lodge of Scotland with Roll of Members, 1734-1934, by Robert Strathern Lindsay, W.S., Edinburgh, 1935. Vol.II, p.639.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-richard-hutchinson | the Earl of Donoughmore }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | rows=2 | before=[[Robert Lowe, 1st Viscount Sherbrooke|Robert Lowe]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Paymaster General]] | years=1858\u20131859}}\n{{s-aft | rows=2 | after=[[Algernon Percy, 6th Duke of Northumberland|Lord Lovaine]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Vice-President of the Board of Trade]] | years=1858\u20131859}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Joseph Warner Henley]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[President of the Board of Trade]] | years=1859}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Thomas Milner Gibson]]}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Hely-Hutchinson, 3rd Earl of Donoughmore|John Hely-Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Earl of Donoughmore]] | years=1851\u20131866}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[John Hely-Hutchinson, 5th Earl of Donoughmore|John Hely-Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Paymaster General}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donoughmore, Richard Hely-Hutchinson, 4th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Paymasters General]]\n[[Category:Hely-Hutchinson family|Richard]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Board of Trade]]\n[[Category:Earls of Donoughmore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Donoughmore \n| honorific-suffix = [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order1 = [[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| term_start1 = 3 March 1859\n| term_end1 = 11 June 1859\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 14th Earl of Derby|The Earl of Derby]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Joseph Warner Henley]]\n| successor1 = [[Thomas Milner Gibson]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|4 April 1823|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|22 February 1866|4 April 1823}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]  \n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = Thomasina Steele (d. 1890) \n}}\n\n'''Richard John Hely-Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore''' [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (4 April 1823 \u2013 22 February 1866), styled '''Viscount Suirdale''' between 1832 and 1851, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nDonoughmore was the son of [[John Hely-Hutchinson, 3rd Earl of Donoughmore]], and the Hon. Margaret, daughter of [[Luke Gardiner, 1st Viscount Mountjoy]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11063.htm |title= thepeerage.com Richard John Hely Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore of Knocklofty |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nDonoughmore was appointed [[High Sheriff of Tipperary]] for 1847.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.freemasonry.london.museum/os/wp-content/resources/frs_freemasons_complete_jan2012.pdf| title = Fellows of the Royal Society who are or were Freemasons, listed alphabetically| accessdate = 2012-11-09| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121202144502/http://www.freemasonry.london.museum/os/wp-content/resources/frs_freemasons_complete_jan2012.pdf| archivedate = 2012-12-02}}</ref>\n\nHe entered the [[House of Lords]] on the death of his father in 1851. He held office as [[Vice-President of the Board of Trade]] and [[Paymaster General]] in [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 14th Earl of Derby|Lord Derby]]'s [[Conservative Government 1858\u20131859|second government]], and was promoted to the actual [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry|presidency of the Board of Trade]] in February 1859 on the resignation of [[Joseph Warner Henley|J. W. Henley]] over the abortive 1859 Reform Bill. He remained in this post until the government fell in June of the same year. In 1858 he was admitted to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]].<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/22125/pages/1792 ''The London Gazette'', 9 April 1858]</ref>\n\nIn 1865 he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=8&dsqSearch=%28%28Gender%3D%27Male%27%29AND%28Surname%3D%27hutchinson%27%29%29| title = Library and Archive Catalogue|publisher = Royal Society|accessdate = 2012-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Donoughmore married Thomasina Jocelyn, daughter of Walter Steele, in 1847. Their fifth son the Hon. [[Walter Hely-Hutchinson|Sir Walter Hely-Hutchinson]] was a diplomat. Donoughmore died in February 1866, aged 42, and was succeeded in the earldom by his eldest son, [[John Hely-Hutchinson, 5th Earl of Donoughmore|John]]. The Countess of Donoughmore died in May 1890.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11063.htm |title= thepeerage.com Richard John Hely Hutchinson, 4th Earl of Donoughmore of Knocklofty |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>\n\nColonel [[Lewis Vivian Loyd]] was married on 14 August 1879 to Lady Mary Sophia Hely Hutchinson (1854\u20131936), daughter of the 4th Earl of Donoughmore\n,<ref name=\"ThePeerage\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25089.htm#i250890\n|title=Colonel Lewis Vivian Loyd\n|work=ThePeerage.com\n|accessdate=28 June 2010\n}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref> a writer and translator<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.whistler.arts.gla.ac.uk/correspondence/biog/display/?bid=Loyd_M\n|title=Mary S. Loyd, 1854-1936\n|work=The Correspondence of James McNeill Whistler\n|accessdate=28 June 2010\n}}</ref> with whom he had three children: two sons and a daughter.<ref>{{cite book\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9UYYThhRIQC&pg=PA297&lpg=PA297&dq=%22Lewis+Vivian+Loyd%22&source=bl&ots=mnao9-Vbwa&sig=ydTOuJmiAFJvxZg-DZRFyqonfr8&hl=en&ei=dPcoTO22N87KjAf1qtFq&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBQQ6AEwADge#v=onepage&q=%22Lewis%20Vivian%20Loyd%22&f=false\n|title=Plantagenet Roll of the Blood Royal: The Clarence Volume, Containing the Descendants of George, Duke of Clarence\n|last=Melville Henry Massue Ruvigny et Raineval (marquis de)\n|year=1994\n|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com\n|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Freemasonry==\nHe was Intitated in Lodge No.12, in Ireland and was Senior Grand Warden of the Grand Lodge of Ireland for 1846.. He was made an Honorary Member of Lodge Holyrood House (St Luke's), No.44, on 7 January 1846.<ref>A History of the Mason Lodge of Holyrood House (St.Luke's), No.44, holding of the Grand Lodge of Scotland with Roll of Members, 1734-1934, by Robert Strathern Lindsay, W.S., Edinburgh, 1935. Vol.II, p.639.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-richard-hutchinson | the Earl of Donoughmore }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | rows=2 | before=[[Robert Lowe, 1st Viscount Sherbrooke|Robert Lowe]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Paymaster General]] | years=1858\u20131859}}\n{{s-aft | rows=2 | after=[[Algernon Percy, 6th Duke of Northumberland|Lord Lovaine]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Vice-President of the Board of Trade]] | years=1858\u20131859}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Joseph Warner Henley]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[President of the Board of Trade]] | years=1859}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Thomas Milner Gibson]]}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Hely-Hutchinson, 3rd Earl of Donoughmore|John Hely-Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Earl of Donoughmore]] | years=1851\u20131866}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[John Hely-Hutchinson, 5th Earl of Donoughmore|John Hely-Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Paymaster General}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donoughmore, Richard Hely-Hutchinson, 4th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Paymasters General]]\n[[Category:Hely-Hutchinson family|Richard]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Board of Trade]]\n[[Category:Earls of Donoughmore]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: , \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Hely-Hutchinson,_4th_Earl_of_Donoughmore"}
{"title_page": "John Allen Chau", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Allen Chau\n| image              =\n| alt                =\n| caption            =\n| other_names        =\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1991|12|18}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Christian Martyr: John Allen Chau |url=https://www.covenantjourney.org/details/john-allen-chau |publisher=Covenant Journey |date=2018-11-21 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|11|17|1991|12|8}}\n| death_place        = [[North Sentinel Island]], India\n| death_cause        = [[Sentinelese]] tribal attack\n| nationality        = American\n| education          = B.Sc. Health and Exercise Science (Sports Medicine), Oral Roberts University<ref>{{cite web |title=A Man's Last Letter Before Being Killed on a Forbidden Island |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/23/world/asia/andaman-missionary-john-chau.html |work=The New York Times |date=2018-11-23 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n}}\n\n'''John Allen Chau''' was a illegal Christian [[missionary]] who died while attempting to convert the native [[Sentinelese]], one of the world's last uncontacted tribes, to [[Christianity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/22/asia/north-sentinel-island-john-allen-chau-diary-intl/index.html|title='You guys might think I'm crazy': Diary of US 'missionary' reveals last days in remote island|first=Euan |last=McKirdy|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in 1991, in [[Alabama]], United States, Chau was the third and youngest child of Lynda Adams-Chau, an organizer for [[Chi Alpha (Christian Fellowship)|Chi Alpha]], and Patrick Chau, a Chinese-American [[psychiatrist]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/2400030/john-allen-chau-life-death-north-sentinel|title=The Last Days of John Allen Chau|last=Perry|first=Alex|date=2019-07-24|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> His father escaped to [[Hong Kong]] during the [[Cultural Revolution|Chinese Cultural Revolution]], after being forced to give up his artistic training at age 16 to work on a farm, and later immigrated to the United States.<ref name=\"auto2\" /> Patrick learned English by [[Autodidacticism|listening to the radio]], and worked odds jobs before being accepted to study chemistry at the University of Southern California, and medicine at [[Oral Roberts University]].<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\nChau's parents were both Christian, which influenced Chau throughout his life.\n\n== Mission to North Sentinel Island ==\nIn November 2018, Chau embarked on an illegal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/john-allen-chau-detailed-efforts-convert-islanders-christianity/story?id=59401238|title=John Allen Chau detailed efforts to convert islanders to Christianity in final diary entries: 'You guys might think I'm crazy'|last=|first=|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> mission to [[North Sentinel Island]], which he considered to be \"[[Satan]]'s last stronghold on Earth,\" with the aim of contacting and living among the Sentinelese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wonderingeagle.wordpress.com/2018/12/08/john-allen-chau-is-no-jim-elliot-the-story-of-john-chau-illustrates-the-dangers-of-indoctrination-in-evangelical-culture-and-being-naive/|title=John Allen Chau is No Jim Elliot. The Story of John Chau Illustrates the Dangers of Indoctrination in Evangelical Culture and Being Na\u00efve|last=wonderingeagle|date=2018-12-08|website=Wondering Eagle|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/incidents/police-faceoff-with-sentinelese-tribe-as-they-struggle-to-recover-slain-missionarys-body/news-story/a88d3780059939a5e11ebcfb556327ac|title=Police face-off with hostile tribe|date=2018-11-25|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> He expressed a strong desire to preach Christianity to the tribe.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/religion/2018/11/28/slain-missionary-john-chau-prepared-much-more-than-we-thought-his-case-is-still-quandary-us-missionaries/|title=Perspective {{!}} Slain missionary John Chau prepared much more than we thought, but are missionaries still fools?|last=Stetzer|first=Ed|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In preparation for the trip, Chau was vaccinated and quarantined,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2018/november-web-only/all-nations-john-allen-chau-north-sentinel-island.html|title=What John Allen Chau's Missions Agency Wants You to Know|last=|first=|website=ChristianityToday.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and also undertook medical and linguistic training.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> However, he did not seek permission from the Indian authorities before embarking; foreign nationals must obtain a permit to visit the [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]], and no one is allowed on North Sentinel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/american-national-john-allen-chau-violated-every-rule-in-the-book-to-meet-the-sentinelese/story-AuB0stXyIR7AY1c2XCNkfN.html|title=American national John Allen Chau violated every rule in the book to meet the Sentinelese|date=2018-11-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Instead, Chau bribed two fishermen [[Indian rupee|Rs]] 25,000 to take him close to the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/us-tourist-john-chau-paid-fishermen-rs-25-000-for-fatal-trip-to-sentinelese-island-1951387|title=American Paid Fishermen Rs. 25,000 For Fatal Trip To Andamans|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The fishermen were later arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/11/23/cops-arrest-suspects-believed-to-help-us-missionary-on-fatal-trip/|title=Cops arrest suspects believed to help US missionary on fatal trip|last=Eustachewich|first=Lia|date=2018-11-23|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nDespite efforts by Indian authorities, which involved a tense encounter with the tribe, Chau's body has still not been recovered.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Ultimately, Indian officials concluded that the risk of a dangerous clash between investigators and islanders was too great to justify further attempts to recover the body. Indian officials made several attempts to recover Chau's body but eventually abandoned those efforts. An anthropologist involved in the case told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that the risk of a dangerous clash between investigators and the islanders was too great to justify any further attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/28/india-body-john-allen-chau-missionary-killed-by-sentinelese-tribe|title=India has no plans to recover body of US missionary killed by tribe|author1=Michael Safi|author2=Denis Giles|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 November 2018}}</ref> His death is officially listed as a murder, though both the Indian and the American governments have stated that they will not press charges against the native Sentinelese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladbible.com/news/news-us-will-not-seek-to-prosecute-tribe-that-killed-missionary-20190220|title=US Will Not Seek To Prosecute North Sentinelese Tribe That Killed Missionary|website=www.ladbible.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Chau was the subject of significant criticism for his perceived recklessness in visiting the island despite the possibility of introducing deadly pathogens to the native Sentinelese.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/john-allen-chau-was-brave-he-was-also-reckless/2018/11/27/ddb9200c-f1b0-11e8-99c2-cfca6fcf610c_story.html|title=John Allen Chau was brave. He was also reckless.|newspaper=The Washington Post|last1=Elonai|first1=Maisha|date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.survivalinternational.org/news/12031|title=Survival International statement on killing of American man John Allen Chau by Sentinelese tribe, Andaman Islands|website=Survival International|date=November 21, 2018|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chau, John Allen}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oral Roberts University alumni]]\n[[Category:American Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:People murdered in India]]\n[[Category:American people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Murdered missionaries]]\n[[Category:American people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Allen Chau\n| image              =\n| alt                =\n| caption            =\n| other_names        =\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1991|12|18}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Christian Martyr: John Allen Chau |url=https://www.covenantjourney.org/details/john-allen-chau |publisher=Covenant Journey |date=2018-11-21 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|11|17|1991|12|8}}\n| death_place        = [[North Sentinel Island]], India\n| death_cause        = [[Sentinelese]] tribal attack\n| nationality        = American\n| education          = B.Sc. Health and Exercise Science (Sports Medicine), Oral Roberts University<ref>{{cite web |title=A Man's Last Letter Before Being Killed on a Forbidden Island |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/23/world/asia/andaman-missionary-john-chau.html |work=The New York Times |date=2018-11-23 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n}}\n\n'''John Allen Chau''' was a Christian [[missionary]] who died while attempting to convert the native [[Sentinelese]], one of the world's last uncontacted tribes, to [[Christianity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/22/asia/north-sentinel-island-john-allen-chau-diary-intl/index.html|title='You guys might think I'm crazy': Diary of US 'missionary' reveals last days in remote island|first=Euan |last=McKirdy|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in 1991, in [[Alabama]], United States, Chau was the third and youngest child of Lynda Adams-Chau, an organizer for [[Chi Alpha (Christian Fellowship)|Chi Alpha]], and Patrick Chau, a Chinese-American [[psychiatrist]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/2400030/john-allen-chau-life-death-north-sentinel|title=The Last Days of John Allen Chau|last=Perry|first=Alex|date=2019-07-24|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> His father escaped to [[Hong Kong]] during the [[Cultural Revolution|Chinese Cultural Revolution]], after being forced to give up his artistic training at age 16 to work on a farm, and later immigrated to the United States.<ref name=\"auto2\" /> Patrick learned English by [[Autodidacticism|listening to the radio]], and worked odds jobs before being accepted to study chemistry at the University of Southern California, and medicine at [[Oral Roberts University]].<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\nChau's parents were both Christian, which influenced Chau throughout his life.\n\n== Mission to North Sentinel Island ==\nIn November 2018, Chau embarked on an illegal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/john-allen-chau-detailed-efforts-convert-islanders-christianity/story?id=59401238|title=John Allen Chau detailed efforts to convert islanders to Christianity in final diary entries: 'You guys might think I'm crazy'|last=|first=|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> mission to [[North Sentinel Island]], which he considered to be \"[[Satan]]'s last stronghold on Earth,\" with the aim of contacting and living among the Sentinelese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wonderingeagle.wordpress.com/2018/12/08/john-allen-chau-is-no-jim-elliot-the-story-of-john-chau-illustrates-the-dangers-of-indoctrination-in-evangelical-culture-and-being-naive/|title=John Allen Chau is No Jim Elliot. The Story of John Chau Illustrates the Dangers of Indoctrination in Evangelical Culture and Being Na\u00efve|last=wonderingeagle|date=2018-12-08|website=Wondering Eagle|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/incidents/police-faceoff-with-sentinelese-tribe-as-they-struggle-to-recover-slain-missionarys-body/news-story/a88d3780059939a5e11ebcfb556327ac|title=Police face-off with hostile tribe|date=2018-11-25|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> He expressed a strong desire to preach Christianity to the tribe.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/religion/2018/11/28/slain-missionary-john-chau-prepared-much-more-than-we-thought-his-case-is-still-quandary-us-missionaries/|title=Perspective {{!}} Slain missionary John Chau prepared much more than we thought, but are missionaries still fools?|last=Stetzer|first=Ed|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In preparation for the trip, Chau was vaccinated and quarantined,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2018/november-web-only/all-nations-john-allen-chau-north-sentinel-island.html|title=What John Allen Chau's Missions Agency Wants You to Know|last=|first=|website=ChristianityToday.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and also undertook medical and linguistic training.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> However, he did not seek permission from the Indian authorities before embarking; foreign nationals must obtain a permit to visit the [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]], and no one is allowed on North Sentinel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/american-national-john-allen-chau-violated-every-rule-in-the-book-to-meet-the-sentinelese/story-AuB0stXyIR7AY1c2XCNkfN.html|title=American national John Allen Chau violated every rule in the book to meet the Sentinelese|date=2018-11-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Instead, Chau bribed two fishermen [[Indian rupee|Rs]] 25,000 to take him close to the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/us-tourist-john-chau-paid-fishermen-rs-25-000-for-fatal-trip-to-sentinelese-island-1951387|title=American Paid Fishermen Rs. 25,000 For Fatal Trip To Andamans|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The fishermen were later arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/11/23/cops-arrest-suspects-believed-to-help-us-missionary-on-fatal-trip/|title=Cops arrest suspects believed to help US missionary on fatal trip|last=Eustachewich|first=Lia|date=2018-11-23|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nDespite efforts by Indian authorities, which involved a tense encounter with the tribe, Chau's body has still not been recovered.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Ultimately, Indian officials concluded that the risk of a dangerous clash between investigators and islanders was too great to justify further attempts to recover the body. Indian officials made several attempts to recover Chau's body but eventually abandoned those efforts. An anthropologist involved in the case told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that the risk of a dangerous clash between investigators and the islanders was too great to justify any further attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/28/india-body-john-allen-chau-missionary-killed-by-sentinelese-tribe|title=India has no plans to recover body of US missionary killed by tribe|author1=Michael Safi|author2=Denis Giles|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 November 2018}}</ref> His death is officially listed as a murder, though both the Indian and the American governments have stated that they will not press charges against the native Sentinelese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ladbible.com/news/news-us-will-not-seek-to-prosecute-tribe-that-killed-missionary-20190220|title=US Will Not Seek To Prosecute North Sentinelese Tribe That Killed Missionary|website=www.ladbible.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Chau was the subject of significant criticism for his perceived recklessness in visiting the island despite the possibility of introducing deadly pathogens to the native Sentinelese.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/john-allen-chau-was-brave-he-was-also-reckless/2018/11/27/ddb9200c-f1b0-11e8-99c2-cfca6fcf610c_story.html|title=John Allen Chau was brave. He was also reckless.|newspaper=The Washington Post|last1=Elonai|first1=Maisha|date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.survivalinternational.org/news/12031|title=Survival International statement on killing of American man John Allen Chau by Sentinelese tribe, Andaman Islands|website=Survival International|date=November 21, 2018|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chau, John Allen}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oral Roberts University alumni]]\n[[Category:American Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:People murdered in India]]\n[[Category:American people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Murdered missionaries]]\n[[Category:American people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n", "name_user": "196.15.23.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Allen_Chau"}
{"title_page": "John Fellowes, 4th Baron de Ramsey", "text_new": "{{BLP refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n'''John Ailwyn Fellowes, 4th Baron de Ramsey''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DL}} (born 27 February 1942) is a British landowner, agriculturalist, and the first chairman of the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n==Career==\nLord de Ramsey farms the family's 6,000 acre estate around the village of [[Abbots Ripton]], [[Huntingdonshire]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Property |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/3353100/Village-voice.html |title=Village voice |publisher=Telegraph |date=2006-09-23 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nHe has a longstanding interest in fenland drainage,  acting as a commissioner for the [[Middle Level Commissioners]],  President of the [[Association of Drainage Authorities]] 1991-1994 and 2001-present, and a director of the Cambridge Water Company from 1974\u20131994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angliafarmers.co.uk/content/moreinfo.asp?mid=401 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120722212434/http://www.angliafarmers.co.uk/content/moreinfo.asp?mid=401 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 22, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2012 |title = Saving time & money on agricultural inputs &#124; the AF Group}}</ref>\n\nHe was president of the [[Country Landowners Association]] (1991\u20131993), a [[Crown Estate]] commissioner 1994\u20132002, and president of the [[Royal Agricultural Society of England]] 2002\u201303.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.co.uk/people/biographies/browse/d/17413/John%20Ailwyn%20Fellowes+DE%20RAMSEY.aspx |title=People of Today Index, People of Today, People of Influence &#124; Debrett's |website=Debretts.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther roles include Chairman of the Cambridgeshire Farmers Union (1982), Director of the [[Shuttleworth Trust]] (1982\u20131995), Member of the Governing Body of the [[Institute of Plant Science Research]] (1984\u20131989), Director of [[Strutt and Parker]] (Farms) Limited (from 1993), and Director of the [[Lawes Agricultural Trust]] (from 1996).<ref name=\"cranfield1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page25050.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120723090642/http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page25050.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 23, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2012 |title=Content not found }}</ref> He is chairman of the Lawes Trust which owns the estate on which [[Rothamsted Research]] is based.\n\nIn 1995, Lord de Ramsey became the first chairman of the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n==Family and personal life==\nJohn Ailwyn Fellowes was born in 1942, the elder son of [[Ailwyn Edward Fellowes, 3rd Baron de Ramsey]].  He was educated at [[Maidwell|Maidwell Hall]], Northampton, [[Winchester College]] and [[Writtle College|Writtle Institute of Agriculture]].\n\nIn 1973 he married Phylida Forsyth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p35782.htm#i357814 |title=Person Page 35782 |website=Thepeerage.com |date=1995-05-15 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>{{Verify credibility|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--> They had one son:\n* Hon. Freddie John Fellowes (born 31 May 1978), who as Fred Fellowes runs the [[Secret Garden Party]] music festival each year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Beaumont |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/may/21/festival-secret-garden-party |title=Festivals guide &#124; Festival founders &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nHe married secondly Alison Birkmyre, daughter of [[Birkmyre baronets|Sir Archibald Birkmyre, 3rd Baronet]], in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p14289.htm#i142888 |title=Person Page 14289 |website=Thepeerage.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>{{Verify credibility|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--> The couple has three children:\n* Hon. Charles Henry Fellowes  b. 1986\n*Hon. Daisy Lilah Fellowes  b. 1988\n*Hon. Flora Mary Fellowes  b. 1991.\n\nThe family lives at Abbots Ripton Hall, Huntingdonshire. \n\nIn 1997 Lord de Ramsey was awarded an honorary degree of Doctor of Science from the School of Agriculture, Food and Environment of [[Cranfield University]].<ref name=\"cranfield1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Ailwyn Fellowes, 3rd Baron de Ramsey|Ailwyn Edward Fellowes]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Baron de Ramsey]] | years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:de Ramsey, John Ailwyn Fellows, 4th Baron}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British farmers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Cambridgeshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n'''John Ailwyn Fellowes, 4th Baron de Ramsey''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DL}} (born 27 February 1942) is a British landowner, agriculturalist, and the first chairman of the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n==Career==\nLord de Ramsey farms the family\u2019s 6,000 acre estate around the village of [[Abbots Ripton]], [[Huntingdonshire]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Property |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/3353100/Village-voice.html |title=Village voice |publisher=Telegraph |date=2006-09-23 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nHe has a longstanding interest in fenland drainage,  acting as a commissioner for the [[Middle Level Commissioners]],  President of the [[Association of Drainage Authorities]] 1991-1994 and 2001-present, and a director of the Cambridge Water Company from 1974-1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angliafarmers.co.uk/content/moreinfo.asp?mid=401 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120722212434/http://www.angliafarmers.co.uk/content/moreinfo.asp?mid=401 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 22, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2012 |title = Saving time & money on agricultural inputs &#124; the AF Group}}</ref>\n\nHe was president of the [[Country Landowners Association]] (1991\u20131993), a [[Crown Estate]] commissioner 1994-2002, and president of the [[Royal Agricultural Society of England]] 2002-03.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.co.uk/people/biographies/browse/d/17413/John%20Ailwyn%20Fellowes+DE%20RAMSEY.aspx |title=People of Today Index, People of Today, People of Influence &#124; Debrett's |website=Debretts.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther roles include Chairman of the Cambridgeshire Farmers Union (1982), Director of the [[Shuttleworth Trust]] (1982\u20131995), Member of the Governing Body of the [[Institute of Plant Science Research]] (1984\u20131989), Director of [[Strutt and Parker]] (Farms) Limited (from 1993), and Director of the [[Lawes Agricultural Trust]] (from 1996).<ref name=\"cranfield1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page25050.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120723090642/http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page25050.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 23, 2012 |accessdate=March 18, 2012 |title=Content not found }}</ref> He is chairman of the Lawes Trust which owns the estate on which [[Rothamsted Research]] is based.\n\nIn 1995, Lord de Ramsey became the first chairman of the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n==Family and personal life==\nJohn Ailwyn Fellowes was born in 1942, the elder son of [[Ailwyn Edward Fellowes, 3rd Baron de Ramsey]].  He was educated at [[Maidwell|Maidwell Hall]], Northampton, [[Winchester College]] and [[Writtle College|Writtle Institute of Agriculture]].\n\nIn 1973 he married Phylida Forsyth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p35782.htm#i357814 |title=Person Page 35782 |website=Thepeerage.com |date=1995-05-15 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>{{Verify credibility|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--> They had one son:\n* Hon. Freddie John Fellowes (born 31 May 1978), who as Fred Fellowes runs the [[Secret Garden Party]] music festival each year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Beaumont |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/may/21/festival-secret-garden-party |title=Festivals guide &#124; Festival founders &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\nHe married secondly Alison Birkmyre, daughter of [[Birkmyre baronets|Sir Archibald Birkmyre, 3rd Baronet]], in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p14289.htm#i142888 |title=Person Page 14289 |website=Thepeerage.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>{{Verify credibility|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--> The couple has three children:\n* Hon. Charles Henry Fellowes  b. 1986\n*Hon. Daisy Lilah Fellowes  b. 1988\n*Hon. Flora Mary Fellowes  b. 1991.\n\nThe family lives at Abbots Ripton Hall, Huntingdonshire. \n\nIn 1997 Lord de Ramsey was awarded an honorary degree of Doctor of Science from the School of Agriculture, Food and Environment of [[Cranfield University]].<ref name=\"cranfield1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[Ailwyn Fellowes, 3rd Baron de Ramsey|Ailwyn Edward Fellowes]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Baron de Ramsey]] | years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:de Ramsey, John Ailwyn Fellows, 4th Baron}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British farmers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party 